Propri√©t√©s de combinaisons

Nous allons d√©montrer quelques propri√©t√©s de combinaisons sans r√©p√©tition.

Propri√©t√© (1) :

\[C^{n-k}_n = \frac{n!}{(n-k)!(n-(n-k)!)} = \frac{n!}{(n-k)!k!} = C^k_n\]

Propri√©t√© (2) : le nombre de choix d‚Äôun √©l√©ment parmi \(n\)

\[C^{1}_n = \begin{pmatrix}n \\ 1\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}n \\ n-1 \end{pmatrix} = C^{n-1}_n = n\]

Propri√©t√© (3) :

\[C^{k}_n = C^{k-1}_{n-1} + C^{k}_{n-1}\]

D√©montrons :

\[C^{k-1}_{n-1} = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left((n-1) - (k-1)\right)!} = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k\right)!}\]

\[C^{k}_{n-1} = \frac{(n-1)!}{k! \left((n-1) - k)\right)!} = \frac{(n-1)!}{k! \left(n- k-1\right)!}\] Alors :

\[C^{k-1}_{n-1} + C^{k}_{n-1} = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k\right)!} + \frac{(n-1)!}{k! \left(n- k-1\right)!} = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k-1\right)!}\left(\frac{1}{n-k} + \frac{1}{k}\right) =\] \[= \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k-1\right)!}\left(\frac{k}{(n-k)k} + \frac{n-k}{k(n-k)}\right) = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k-1\right)!}\times \frac{k + n - k}{(n-k)k} =\]

\[ = \frac{(n-1)!}{(k-1)! \left(n- k-1\right)!}\times \frac{n}{(n-k)k} = \frac{(n-1)!\times n}{\left((k-1)!\times k\right) \left((n- k-1)!\times (n-k)\right)} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!} = C^k_n\]

Propri√©t√© (4) :

\[C^{k}_{n} + C^{k+1}_{n} = \begin{pmatrix} n \\ k \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} n \\ k+1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} n+1 \\ k+1 \end{pmatrix} = C^{k+1}_{n+1}\]

D√©montrons :

\[C^{k}_{n} + C^{k+1}_{n} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!} + \frac{n!}{(k+1)!(n-(k+1))!} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k-1)!}\times \left(\frac{1}{n-k} +\frac{1}{k+1}\right) =\]

\[=\frac{n!}{k!(n-k-1)!}\times \left(\frac{k+1}{(n-k)(k+1)} + \frac{n-k}{(k+1)(n-k)}\right) = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k-1)!}\times \left(\frac{k+1 + n-k}{(n-k)(k+1)}\right) =\] \[= \frac{n!}{k!(n-k-1)!}\times \frac{n+1}{(n-k)(k+1)} = \frac{n!\times (n+1)}{\left(k!\times (k+1)\right) \left((n-k-1)! \times (n-k)\right)} = \frac{(n+1)!}{(k+1)!(n-k)!} =\]

\[=\frac{(n+1)!}{(k+1)!\left((n+1) - (k+1)\right)!} = C^{k+1}_{n+1}\]

Propri√©t√© (5) : Formule du bin√¥me : \(\forall (a,b) \in \mathbb{R}^2\) (ensemble des couples de nombres r√©els), \(\forall n \in \mathbb{N}\) :

\[(a+b)^n = \sum^{n}_{k=0}C^k_na^kb^{n-k}\] \(C^k_n\) est aussi appel√© coefficient binomial.

Consid√©rons un exemple de \(n=2\) :

\[(a+b)^2 = C^0_2 a^0 b^{2-0} + C^1_2 a^1 b^{2-1} + C^2_2 a^2 b^{2-2} = C^0_2 a^0 b^{2} + C^1_2 a^1 b^{1} + C^2_2 a^2 b^{0} = C^0_2 b^{2} + C^1_2 ab + C^2_2 a^2 =\]

\[=\frac{2!}{0!(2-0)!}\times b^2 + \frac{2!}{1!(2-1)!}\times ab + \frac{2!}{2!(2-2)!}\times a^2 = b^2 + 2ab + a^2\]
